.TH "usb_get_current_frame_number" 9 "usb_get_current_frame_number" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
usb_get_current_frame_number \- return current bus frame number
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" usb_get_current_frame_number
.BI "(struct usb_device *dev "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "dev" 12
the device whose bus is being queried
.SH "RETURN"
The current frame number for the USB host controller used
with the given USB device. This can be used when scheduling
isochronous requests.
.SH "NOTE"
Different kinds of host controller have different "scheduling
horizons". While one type might support scheduling only 32 frames
into the future, others could support scheduling up to 1024 frames
into the future.
